Alright, I guess I'm being the devil's advocate here.
With the current approach where we dropped filesystem and vmware_datastore from the mapping, there is a downside I think. 

What if the same config option is used somewhere else in the code? Then, the sanitization/conversion needs to be performed there as well. If the redundant mappings stay in the dictionary, I guess it takes care of both filesystem and file. But, that's assuming the same mapping is used. If the mapping is populated again, it's a different story.

This config opt is currently not used in the code anywhere else, so we are good. But, just throwing it out there.

Patch Set 9:

Hemanth, thinking on similar lines, I had submitted my patch yesterday. 
But thinking more about it this morning, it makes sense for this approach as there is only once that the list value of this conf opt is iterated across and the mapping dictionary is used after that to match the schemes and locations.
Uploaded patch set 10.

Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Patch Set 10:

I'm kind of worried about Hemanth's "devil's advocate" argument on PS9.  But including the incorrect names in the mapping still cause a problem in the code, because you'll have to check that the first scheme found when the reverse lookup is done is giving you a value that glance_store recognizes (rather than the incorrect name that's also mapped to the scheme that was looked up).  So no matter how we do this, it's not a clean fix.

My opinion is that this whole part of the code using the map is ill-conceived (what happens if multiple stores can implement the same scheme?), and is going to eventually have to be rewritten anyway.  But I'm not sure that's a helpful observation at the moment.

Patch Set 10:

Brian, if we were to include the incorrect store names in the mapping dictionary, I had added lines 107, 108 to ensure that we would be returned the correct store name anyway when the scheme was matched. 
So if multiple store names use the same scheme, the correct store name would have been taken anyway if the correct names were added to the dictionary after the incorrect names. 
However since the opt's list value is used once to iterate over and reorder the locations based on it (by matching the locations to the schemes in the mapping dictionary), the recent PS just has replacing the incorrect names in the dictionary with the correct names.

Patch Set 19:

About the deprecation ... this is a weird one, because we are deprecating particular values, not deprecating the option itself.  I guess an alternative would be to deprecate this option and introduce a corresponding option that only accepted the correct values via a 'choices' argument to oslo.config?  That seems a bit drastic, but it would conform with the normal process for deprecating a config option.

With respect to "Do we want to deprecate these values?", I think that we do.  Right now we have custom code to translate properly, but I believe if another location strategy that used store names were introduced, it would need the translation code, too.  I think it's better to just get rid of these so we can pretend this situation never happened.
